As @balajis likes to point out, we need to think about the incentives behind the institutions behind the narratives. 5/5

The claim that BAYC founders are rich and should therefore be held accountable for things they haven't done is interesting but probably BS, and might be fun to debate if it wasn't coming from a company worth $600m with a business model of getting people to click on links. 4/5

Click-based business models for journalism (i.e. financed by ads) is the modern update of those trashy magazines that lined a checkout register in the supermarket that had literal lies about celebrities on the front cover, hiding behind 'we need to protect our sources.' 3/5

Too many people hide behind the label of 'journalism' as an inherent moral good. Journalism can obviously be wonderful for the world in many many contexts, but it can also be a force for harm, and the sooner we can get away from click-based business models, the better. 2/5

I do agree that if the BAYC founders wanted to stay anon, they shouldn't have started a legal entity connected to the brand in their actual names, but I also think it's lame that you can out some people who don't want to be outed due to your business model of getting clicks. 1/5 https://t.co/bEm1WQG2jd
